<div type="translation" resp="part:emfr">
                
                
<p n="1">
                        
<supplied reason="lost">Prosperity!</supplied> Fortune!
                </p>
                
                
<p n="1-2">
                        Twelfth year of the victorious king Nandivikramavarman.
                </p>
                
                
<p n="2-7">
                        Viṉaiyīttaṉ, the son-in-law 
<supplied reason="subaudible">of</supplied> 
<unclear>Bāṇa</unclear> Muttaraiyar, fell fighting upon 
<supplied reason="explanation">
  <foreign>mēl</foreign>
</supplied> 
<gap reason="ellipsis" /> 
<supplied reason="explanation">
  <foreign>kutirai muṭṭaṉi</foreign>
</supplied> in the battlefield 
<supplied reason="explanation">
  <foreign>kaḷam</foreign>
</supplied> 
<supplied reason="subaudible">with</supplied> Poṉṉērar, when Kampaṭikaḷ alias Vicaiyātittaṉ
<note>That is, Sanskrit Vijayāditya.</note> marched
<note>literally: “went”.</note> 
<supplied reason="subaudible">with his</supplied> army upon Muruṅkai, in the Ātaiyāṟunāṭu of the Paṭuvūrkkōṭṭam.
                </p>
                
                
<p n="7-13">
                        To him
<note>That is, “in honour of him”.</note>, 
<unclear>having given</unclear> Viṇṭal Paṭṭi and Cemmār Paṭṭi 
<gap reason="ellipsis" />
                </p>
                
                
<p>
                        
<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line" />
                </p>
                
                
<p n="14">
                        He who destroys
<note>That is, “harms”.</note> this 
<supplied reason="subaudible">donation</supplied> 
<supplied reason="lost">he will go to</supplied> 
<unclear>hell ?</unclear> 
<supplied reason="explanation">
  <foreign>nara</foreign>
  <note>That is, a lacunose form of 
  <foreign>narakam</foreign>.</note>
</supplied>.
                </p>
                
